haos tracks how a small, underfunded group of organizers transformed into an unconventional corporation with a ten-million-dollar budget and two thousand volunteers. Over the years, Burning Man’s organizers have experimented with different management models; learned how to recruit, motivate, and retain volunteers; and developed strategies to handle regulatory agencies and respond to media coverage. This remarkable evolution, Chen reveals, offers important lessons for managers in any organization, particularly in uncertain times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArt festivalszNevadaxManagement. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aburning man, community, art, self expression, united states of america, american culture, sociology, sociological, black rock desert, countercultural arts, management models, unconventional, recruitment, motivation, volunteers, managers, festivals, nevada, media coverage, regulation, regulatory organizations, criticisms, legitimacy, radical inclusion, decommodification, communal effort, civic responsibility, participation, immediacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022610237540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226102399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226102399/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles